segments.text: I had the students do this scenario.
I had a gentleman that was a little bit strange, but he had been a corps commander at one time.
And he comes in wearing a saber, and I'm thinking he's going to really give us something.
He pulls the saber out.
He's running around the classroom with that saber, and I'm saying, is he going to stab somebody?
He got someone fired up in his presentation.
And I'm thinking, do I stop this or what do I do?
That was one of the most disconcerting things that ever happened to me.
Later it was kind of funny, but at the time I'm thinking, he was so pumped up and fired up, he was jabbing at this, he'd say the Senate does this or the state does this.
It was sort of an anti-government kind of presentation, even though he was supposed to be successful in those kinds of things.
I think he'd probably just gone through a divorce and the courts had ripped him out.
That was a
I've often thought about, and that taught me a lesson about what a person can bring into a class and what they're going to do in a presentation.
I've had some fun times, too, when I'll have scenarios.
One time I said, all right, you've got to be creative with your scenario.
Well, here they come.
My class is right down the hall.
Here they come carrying a guy in on a gurney.
Covered up.
all this equipment hanging off of him.
Well, they had frozen him in time.
So he sets up with a sheet on his head, you know, all white like a dead man.
They pull the sheet down and push a few buttons, you know, and he rubs the stuff off his face, and then he goes into his, you know, what's happened to the world since he was frozen.
That was one of the great ones, I think.
What about...
Oh, you know, we hear all kinds of stories about excuses given.
I, you know, I've never really had any that come to mind that were absurd.
I have students who are coming, they can't make it because the school board president called them, they couldn't come the last second, or...
I'm new dog it eat my homework kind of stuff.
I haven't had much of that those kinds of things at this level.
No excuses.
I try early on and say that you're gonna miss a class.
Professionals will have to do that.
Just let me know beforehand.
I want you to bring a tape recorder to one of your friends the week before.
Don't expect notes to do the job.
I want you to tape what goes on in class.
And they've really been good at that for the last 20 some odd years.
So unless I'm totally naive, I have not had much problem with even worrying about excuses.
They'll commute from San Antonio quite often.
Three hours, that's a tough drive.
Austin, quite frequently.
We have a doctoral program where we have actually bypassed the University of Texas because they didn't have an EDD program.
They had the old traditional PhD program.
We got this through the work of David Erlandson and some others.
We've got these awesome cohort principals coming in here and doing their doctorate.
And their superintendent gives them every other Friday off to do that.
But then I have students driving in from Waco probably each week.
as far as over in East Texas, Beaumont.
Yes, yes.
And now we're doing a cohort master's program with Sy Ferry right on this side of Houston.
We have several from Prairie View in our doctoral program in the community.
That's a nice run now, about 50 minutes with a 290 over.
But the other side of Houston, not much.
They'll go to U of H or Clear Lake.
Well, I think the research on culture and climate of schools has got a lot of visibility.
I've developed some instruments on measuring ambience or feeling.
The research on a book that I did on

co-authored with Fenwick English and Betty Steffi, Skills for 21st Century School Leaders, Skills for Successful 21st Century School Leaders, where we had to do a lot of research on what the big issues were, what the research is telling us about the kind of skills that leaders need.
And I think probably then the work, the research that I've done on future studies and making it applicable
to success of individuals and corporations, those areas.
I've written quite a bit in those areas.
Probably at Texas A&M since 75, I'd say roughly 50, 55 maybe.
Professor at UTA.
He won the National Dissertation Award.
I'm sorry, UTSA, San Antonio.
I'm sorry, good point.
Yeah, he's just gone to University of Texas, San Antonio.
His dissertation was, and I don't take all the credit for that, we co-chaired that, Jim McNamara and I co-chaired it.
It won the AERA Dissertation of the Year Award and the NCPEA Professor's Year Award.
Very proud of him.
Proud of John Wilson, superintendent of schools down in Clear Creek.
Very proud of the Belton superintendent, Harold Rahm.
H-M?
R-A-M-M, yeah.
And Jim Boyle, superintendent of schools in Temple.
They've done extremely well.
I've got students, a superintendent in Greenville, students, deputy superintendents up in, two of them up in Louisville.
In fact, I'll be going up there soon to work with that school.
Those are some of the notables.
Others are in higher education, different places.
Elaine Wilmore.
is running at the UTA Arlington program as one of my proteges.
So those are some that I'm really proud of.
Let's make believe now you're the new consultant to the Texas A&M administration as to what it ought to do about for the College of Education.
Okay.
I think the first thing the president and the provost
In spite of the, we have a university system initiative now to create, make it possible to produce more teachers and get the whole system involved in that.
But one of the first things I would do without question is say this university, one of its highest priorities, is to develop the finest teachers that have ever been developed.
That it's an entire university responsibility.
that the sciences and the liberal arts, we're going to try to select the best and brightest to come into teaching.
We're obviously going to push for higher salaries.
But we want the finest teaching force.
And I think the president, the provost, and the other deans may fight that if they're going to lose money.
But if they weren't going to lose money, I think they would get behind that.
And same thing for public school administrators.
And work with the College of Business, perhaps with sociology and the Bush School on Public Affairs,
and develop a kind of leadership program for schools that would be the best in the world.
Okay, now you're the consultant now to the College of Education.
Okay.
I think the College of Education right now, in my opinion, exists, it has multiple missions, but its primary mission is to improve the teaching
administration, counseling for public schools of Texas and the nation.
We have people majoring in things in this college that has no interest in or no link to public education.

I would take a close look at that and say if you're in a college of education, we should be one way or another interested in using our talents to make sure that every child in this state had the kind of education
that they deserved, your child and other child.
And that everyone in this college is involved one way or another.
Whether you're an ed psych specialist who's looking at some specific little element, you ought to be looking at how that can improve public schools and public education.
And I would not probably be a popular dean by doing that,
But to me, we've got to focus more on our primary mission, and that's improving the schools of Texas.
And in doing so, we improve the private schools.
We improve, we develop professors that can go into the other universities with the same mindset that public schools are the primary thing.
Even though I might be able to write and do things that are not related to improving schools, my primary mission would be to help schools improve, be proud to be in education,
make sure that I had an impact on what happened in the public schools of Texas.
What role, if any, should this department play in regard to the homeschool trend and or the small privacy?
Well, our role, I think, is to encourage any alternative that will help a child as long as it's not violating the Constitution.

As long as these homeschool programs are helping children, as long as private schools are helping children, we should prepare leaders for those, teachers for those, and be totally supportive of alternative programs.
Charter schools, more the better as long as they really meet the state requirements and give children alternatives and teachers alternatives.
Okay, I hear the end.
Do you think of some things we haven't touched on?
No, you've been very thorough, very thorough.
If we had all the people in your A&M years here, to whom would you be expressing your greatest gratitude and why?
Yeah.
Well, first and foremost would have to be Dr. Paul Hensarling.
He pulled me away from science, the National Science Foundation programs,
Somebody told me what a wonderful person he was, and I came over and met him for about 30 minutes.
I changed my major.
Because he said, John, science is fine, but the excitement in the world in your lifetime is going to be in education.
You need to be out front and be a part of that.
He's the one that's always told me to be better than you think you can be.
He's the one that took interest in Carolyn and the family.
He's the one that wrote beautifully and contacted superintendents all over the state when they accomplished something.
They knew him.
He knew more people at that time in my life than anybody.
So he would have to be one.
Dr. Bob Randall, who came here as a young professor out of the University of Texas, was just as country as he could be, but he was brilliant in measurement.
And he had done some work on problem attack behavior and decision making.
And I didn't want to do anything on how to keep your lunch line straight or the bus routes in Texas.
I wanted social science because it just was really hot now in understanding schools and school leadership.

And he let me come in on his research and dovetailed on problem-attack behavior and its relationship to the sex prior teaching experience and college preparation of selected elementary school principals, a proposal you read a few years ago.
Very instrumental in getting me into the behavioral science research end of it and gearing me really toward the research side of it.
Those two were very, very important to me.
And then I think, too, looking back on it, Chuck Sampson.
and Marvin Tate appointing me, you know, to the athletic council.
Because I was thinking about taking off, doing a deanship thing and leaving A&M at the time and that gave me a place to stay and I'll always respect Chuck for that.
I've had colleagues here too that made it livable around here.
Bob Stalkup, who was here, who was in our position as a higher education professor, who's now retired up in Virginia.
Dr. David Erlandson, whom I was responsible for bringing here as chairing a search committee after one year here.
David is very notable, I think.
And Brian Cole.
Brian, our department head right now, is the model department head.
He's going to be involved halftime with the president on the bonfire thing.
We've merged departments.
He's very much into the whole continuous improvement quality stuff.
But he has, where I had a disaster department head before him.
She had never been appointed, but she was appointed over the wishes of us.
The Stallings had appointed her, even though the votes were strong for another individual who left the university.
When Brian came in, there wasn't any of this, I'm going to catch you doing something.
there was this, I'm going to help you succeed and encourage you along the way.
But it hadn't stopped him from becoming well-known as well.
So I guess in terms of the campus itself, those are the individuals that really stand out.
Another person that goes way back, who's long dead now, John Millef.
When I was an undergraduate here,
He told me when I was running around hell raising, thinking about good bull stories that later emerged.
I remember one time I got to know him through a friend of mine.
I wasn't in veterinary medicine.
I remember he told me when I was struggling trying to make grades to stay in school.
He says, John Hoyle, you've got what it takes to graduate from Texas A&M.
At the time, I didn't believe him.
At the end of the four years, I walked down the steps.
There he was.
I didn't even, I never had him as a prof. 1967, Ph.D., he was at the bottom of the stairs.
He and John and Ruth Milliff were key players along those years, even though I never had them.
They were great mentors, great people.
And I went to see them in their failing years, and I'll always respect that.
What was his nickname?
It was Dr. Milliff to me.
Is that right?
Yeah.
I'm trying to remember.
He was an icon.
I was just a little old nobody.
In all these years, the best moments, the joyful moments, what were some of those?
I think probably graduation day in 1957, mother and dad here, being the first boy with an official degree.
My sister was here and Carolyn.
We were married soon after that.
joyous moment.
Finished the PhD was a joyous moment.
They were here and dad gave me a little briefcase I remember.
Professionally, of course, personally, in terms of my children, all those kinds of things and graduating, seeing them succeed, been very joyous.
And then last, last summer, being selected by my colleagues around the nation for the first
Living Legend Award in our field.
And what an honor that was, not deserving, but one that really was a joyous time.
And there were people far more scholarly, but somehow I lucked out and got it.
And we made it even more meaningful this year when Jack Culbertson got it, who had created UCEA and really been the father of our field the last 40 years.
But those were joyous kinds of moments.
And I've gotten a couple of Distinguished Teaching Awards here.

that, you know, it's a great feeling, but there's also others who deserved it that don't get it because, I'm not saying it's political, but it's such a timing thing sometimes, and anybody who gets one of them deserves it, but there's so many others who do, so I'm not sure it's a peer type of thing, you know what I mean?
It's a great award, and I'm glad I got them, but the other things brought me more joy.
Let's make believe a stranger walks up to you and hands you a check for a million dollars with one condition.
You must pass it on to Texas A&M, but you've got to decide how they spend the money.
What would you ask them to do if you could give them a million dollars?
Yeah.
If I could give them a million dollars, I would obviously say that school leadership is where I want it to be.
I want to be placed on school leadership.
And I want to go in and identify even at the high school level.
Excuse me.
I would say let's identify some of your outstanding young men and women in your high school who have some aspirations for education.
And I would like to see that money spent on scholarships,
and to have a nurturing environment when they enter the university, to have them come all the way at four-year program into education with their idea on being principals or superintendents.
And that's, to me, that's where I wanted to go.
Last question.
What feelings do you have in your heart for Texas A&M today?
I love the institution dearly.
I'm glad I made the decision to get my doctorate here, even though I was at Colorado University.
The only concern I have about Texas A&M, it's still overwhelmingly traditional and conservative.
And where I'm a moderate, I sometimes clash with some of the
I guess I would never, never tell a student not to become a tech student.
If they're interested, I'm going to tell them this is the place to come.
We've got outstanding faculty here.
We've had under Dr. Bowen, I think we've had a good stable leadership
And the 2020 vision project, if Dr. Bowen and his staff can sell that and make that work, that can really be a great opportunity.
But right now, I don't see it grabbing hold.
You know, the dreams are there, but I don't see the action.
I see the faculty standing back and saying, well, this too shall pass.
I'd like to see it implemented and see it happen.
